Figure 1. (a,b) Scanning electron microscope (SEM) images, inset shows millimeter sized as grown single crystals and (c,d) Raman spectra of as-obtained $\mathrm{MnPS}_{3}$ and $\mathrm{FePS}_{3}$ single crystals, respectively.

The X-ray diffraction data (XRD) of the samples were analyzed to study the crystal planes and crystallinity of $\mathrm{MnPS}_{3}$ and $\mathrm{FePS}_{3}$ single crystals. It is evident from Figure 2a,b that these results are well in accordance with the standard JPCDS cards belonging to (PDF\#33-0903, PDF\#30-0663) $\mathrm{MnPS}_{3}$ and $\mathrm{FePS}_{3}$, respectively. The crystal lattice and phase identification revealed that both $\mathrm{MnPS}_{3}$ and $\mathrm{FePS}_{3}$ exhibit high-quality single crystals with major (001) and (002) peaks. The absence of any impurity peak suggests that these samples have pure phases. Inset in Figure 2a,b shows the crystallographic model of $\mathrm{MnPS}_{3}$ and $\mathrm{FePS}_{3}$ along (001) plane, respectively. Figure $2 \mathrm{c}$, d displays the TEM images of $\mathrm{MnPS}_{3}$ and $\mathrm{FePS}_{3}$, suggesting that both samples are highly crystalline with growth as single crystal. The d-spacing

