The chemical composition and bonding state of the samples were studied by using XPS analysis, as shown in Figure 3. The Mn $2 \mathrm{p}$ peaks of $\mathrm{MnPS}_{3}$ detected at $652.8$ and $641 \mathrm{eV}$ can be assigned to $2 \mathrm{p}_{3 / 2}$ and $2 \mathrm{p}_{1 / 2}$, respectively. The $\mathrm{S} 2 \mathrm{p}$, peaks identified at $162.75$ and $163.9 \mathrm{eV}$ can be assigned to $2 \mathrm{p}_{3 / 2}$ and $2 \mathrm{p}_{1 / 2}$. For $\mathrm{P} 2 \mathrm{p}$, two peaks at $132.5 \mathrm{eV}$ and $133.6 \mathrm{eV}$ are assigned to $2 \mathrm{p}_{3 / 2}$ and $2 \mathrm{p}_{1 / 2}$. In case of $\mathrm{FePS}_{3}$, the Fe $2 \mathrm{p}$ peaks at 709 and $722 \mathrm{eV}$ are assigned to $2 \mathrm{p}_{3 / 2}$ and $2 \mathrm{p}_{1 / 2}$. Both $\mathrm{S} 2 \mathrm{p}$ and $\mathrm{P} 2 \mathrm{p}$ peaks of $\mathrm{FePS}_{3}$ show quite similar position and shape as those peaks for $\mathrm{MnPS}_{3}$. All these values are consistent with the previous reports [26,27].

Magnetic susceptibility indicates the magnetic properties of a material. It depicts the degree of magnetization of a material with respect to temperature at constant applied magnetic field. The magnetic susceptibility $(\chi)$ as a function of temperature for both $\mathrm{MnPS}_{3}$ and $\mathrm{FePS}_{3}$ crystals is represented in Figure 4a,b. The susceptibility plots of $\mathrm{MnPS}_{3}$ and $\mathrm{FePS}_{3}$ were examined through field cooling (FC) and zero field cooling (ZFC) curves. From the susceptibility plots, we can observe the isotropic behavior of $\mathrm{MnPS}_{3}$, while for $\mathrm{FePS}_{3}$ a considerable anisotropic trend has been noticed. The susceptibilities of $\mathrm{MnPS}_{3}$ and $\mathrm{FePS}_{3}$ increase with decreasing temperature till at $120 \mathrm{~K}$ and $128 \mathrm{~K}$, respectively. Beyond this point it shows rapid decrease, exhibiting a Curie like tail at lowest temperatures. Furthermore, the susceptibility is seen to follow the Curie-Weiss law at higher temperatures (inset Figure $4 a, b$ ), which is an identification feature of the antiferromagnetic nature of these materials [7]. It can be inferred from Figure $4 a, b$ that Neel temperature for $\mathrm{MnPS}_{3}$ and $\mathrm{FePS}_{3}$ are $78 \mathrm{~K}$ and $123 \mathrm{~K}$, while the corresponding Curie temperatures are found to be at $365 \mathrm{~K}$ and $324 \mathrm{~K}$, respectively. These values of Neel temperature and Curie temperature are well matched with the previous reports [28,29]. The broad maxima above Neel temperature is a result of short-range spin-spin correlation in typical magnetic systems. We can observe that magnetic susceptibility for FC is higher than ZFC throughout the observed range for both $\mathrm{MnPS}_{3}$ and $\mathrm{FePS}_{3}$. The increased Curie temperature beyond room temperature shows that these materials are favorable for spintronic applications.\\
