Figure 5. (a,b) Projected density of states of $\mathrm{MnPS}_{3}$ and $\mathrm{FePS}_{3}(\mathbf{c}, \mathbf{d})$ structure of $\mathrm{MnPS}_{3}$ and $\mathrm{FePS}_{3}$ under incident electromagnetic wave $(\mathbf{e}, \mathbf{f})$ calculated dielectric function for $\mathrm{MnPS}_{3}$ and $\mathrm{FePS}_{3}$, respectively. The frequency-dependent dielectric functions have been calculated using parallel and perpendicular electric field component vectors along the c-axis, as shown in Figure $5 c, d$. The frequency-dependent dielectric functions in Figure 5e,f show a strong isotropic and anisotropic behavior in lower and higher energy ranges for $\mathrm{MnPS}_{3}$ and $\mathrm{FePS}_{3}$, respectively. It was found that $\mathrm{MnPS}_{3}$ shows strong isotropic behavior for perpendicular and parallel polarization at lower and higher energy ranges. On the contrary, $\mathrm{FePS}_{3}$ exhibits a strong anisotropic trend for both perpendicular and parallel polarization with an increased number of peaks for dielectric constants at the given energy range. Moreover, the calculated frequency-dependent dielectric functions show a similar trend between $5 \mathrm{eV}$ to $40 \mathrm{eV}$ and $60 \mathrm{eV}$ to $100 \mathrm{eV}$ with increased number peaks of $\mathrm{FePS}_{3}$ for both perpendicular and parallel polarization as compared to $\mathrm{MnPS}_{3}$, which clearly demonstrates the effect of isotropic and anisotropic trend on $\mathrm{MnPS}_{3}$ and $\mathrm{FePS}_{3}$, respectively.

