\section{Conclusions}
High-quality single crystals of $\mathrm{MnPS}_{3}$ and $\mathrm{FePS}_{3}$ were synthesized by using CVT. The EPR and VSM were used to corroborate the existence of antiferromagnetic behavior and to study isotropy/anisotropy in these materials. The probe for the magnetic character of $\mathrm{MnPS}_{3}$ and $\mathrm{FePS}_{3}$ was carried out at $120 \mathrm{~K}, 200 \mathrm{~K}$ and $300 \mathrm{~K}$. The susceptibility showed a typical antiferromagnetic behavior in $\mathrm{MnPS}_{3}$ with an isotropic trend, while an anisotropic behavior was witnessed for $\mathrm{FePS}_{3}$. Moreover, our calculations further confirmed that the antiferromagnetic state was additionally stable than the ferromagnetic state for both $\mathrm{MnPS}_{3}$ and $\mathrm{FePS}_{3}$. The projected density of states (PDOS) manifested a vital irregularity between spin-up and spin-down channels of $\mathrm{Mn}$ and $\mathrm{Fe} 3 \mathrm{~d}$ states, which is responsible for the primary contribution to the antiferromagnetic states near the Fermi level. The frequency-dependent dielectric function calculations have shown that $\mathrm{MnPS}_{3}$ possessed strong isotropic behavior for both perpendicular polarization and parallel polarization at lower and higher energy ranges. On the contrary, $\mathrm{FePS}_{3}$ exhibited strong anisotropic trend for both perpendicular as well as for parallel polarizations at the given energy range.

